,"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Escrotum\u003C/strong\u003E forms from the fusion of the labioscrotal swellings in male embryos during weeks 9-12 of development. The fusion line is visible as the scrotal raphe. In female embryos, these swellings remain separate and form the labia majora.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options develop from different embryological structures. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epenile urethra\u003C/strong\u003E forms from the urethral groove and urogenital folds. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eperineal raphe\u003C/strong\u003E represents the fusion line of the urogenital folds. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eprepuce\u003C/strong\u003E develops from the genital tubercle. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorpus spongiosum\u003C/strong\u003E develops from mesenchymal tissue surrounding the urethral plate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis fusion process is dependent on androgens, particularly dihydrotestosterone. Failure of fusion can lead to various disorders of sexual development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The labioscrotal swellings fuse in male embryos to form the scrotum during weeks 9-12 of development.","In female embryos, the labioscrotal swellings remain unfused and develop into the labia majora."],"references":["Hutson JM, Li R, Southwell BR, Petersen BL, Thorup J, Cortes D. Germ cell development in the postnatal testis: the key to prevent malignancy in cryptorchidism? Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2013 Jan 3;3:176. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2012.00176. PMID: 23316184; PMCID: PMC3539691.","P A A, Arbor TC, Krishan K. Embryology, Sexual Development. [Updated 2023 Aug 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557601/","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97210"}},"